<ns1146:section xmlns:ns1146="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.ejb.enterpriseBeans.entityBeans.cmp.ejbQuery.queryMethods.queryMethods">

  <ns1147:title xmlns:ns1147="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Query methods</ns1147:title>
  <ns1148:para xmlns:ns1148="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The EJB specification defines 2 types of query methods: 
    <ns1149:itemizedlist xmlns:ns1149="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns1150:listitem xmlns:ns1150="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1151:formalpara xmlns:ns1151="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns1152:title xmlns:ns1152="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Finder methods</ns1152:title>
        <ns1153:para xmlns:ns1153="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
          defined in the home or local-home interface of entity beans which 
          are meant for users of the entity bean and 
        </ns1153:para>
      </ns1151:formalpara></ns1150:listitem>  
      <ns1154:listitem xmlns:ns1154="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1155:formalpara xmlns:ns1155="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns1156:title xmlns:ns1156="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Select methods</ns1156:title>
        <ns1157:para xmlns:ns1157="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
           which are meant only for internal use within the entity bean
          implementation class itself.
        </ns1157:para>
      </ns1155:formalpara></ns1154:listitem>
    </ns1149:itemizedlist>  
  </ns1148:para>  
  <ns1158:para xmlns:ns1158="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The query statements for both of these are defined in the same way using EJB-QL.
  </ns1158:para>
    
  <ns1159:section xmlns:ns1159="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns1160:title xmlns:ns1160="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Defining Finder Methods</ns1160:title>
    <ns1161:para xmlns:ns1161="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      Consider, for example, the local-home interface of our  
      <ns1162:literal xmlns:ns1162="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">WeatherReading</ns1162:literal> bean. It defines 3 finder methods:
<ns1163:programlisting xmlns:ns1163="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" parse="text" href="../../../../../source/WeatherStation/src/businessLogic/WeatherReadingLocalHome.java"/>
</ns1163:programlisting>  
      </ns1161:para>
     <ns1164:para xmlns:ns1164="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The bean implementation does not contain an implementation for these finder methods. The
        implementation will be supplied by the subclass generated by the container. Below we show
        the <ns1165:literal xmlns:ns1165="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">WeatherReadingBean</ns1165:literal> implementation class:
<ns1166:programlisting xmlns:ns1166="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" parse="text" href="../../../../../source/WeatherStation/src/businessLogic/WeatherReadingBean.java"/>
</ns1166:programlisting>  
     </ns1164:para>
     <ns1167:para xmlns:ns1167="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Instead we define the query methods via EJB-QL within the ejb-jar deployment descriptor:
<ns1168:programlisting xmlns:ns1168="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" parse="text" href="../../../../../source/WeatherStation/META-INF/ejb-jar.xml"/>
</ns1168:programlisting>  
   </ns1167:para>
  </ns1159:section>
</ns1146:section>